{
  "id": "q-zk-nullifier-storage",
  "question": "How should a Soroban privacy pool store nullifiers without re-enabling double spends as the set grows?",
  "surface": [
    "skills.stellar-dev.zk-proofs",
    "skills.stellar-dev.smart-contracts",
    "stellarDocs.search_soroban_contract_docs"
  ],
  "golden": {
    "answer": "A spent nullifier must remain enforceable for as long as its note can be accepted. For an exact set, store each domain-separated nullifier as an individually keyed persistent entry with explicit TTL and rent handling; do not put an unbounded map in one instance value or scan the full set. An authenticated root may instead live on-chain, but transition proofs must prove non-membership and insertion, and the witness/history availability model must be specified. Pruning is sound only when the protocol also makes the corresponding old notes unspendable, such as after a bounded epoch withdrawal window.",
    "keyFacts": [
      "Deleting a still-relevant spent nullifier can reopen a double-spend path.",
      "For an exact set, use individually keyed persistent nullifiers with explicit TTL and rent handling, not an unbounded instance map.",
      "An on-chain authenticated root requires sound non-membership/insertion transition proofs and a specified witness/history availability model.",
      "Pruning is sound only when the corresponding old notes are also unspendable."
    ],
    "avoid": [
      "Nullifiers may silently expire or be forgotten after TTL expiry while their notes remain spendable.",
      "An off-chain database alone is sufficient to enforce double-spend prevention.",
      "An unbounded nullifier map should be stored in one instance value or checked by scanning the full set.",
      "Archived or expired state is automatically restored without an explicit restoration and TTL plan."
    ]
  },
